International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Sun 14 Oct 2012
Source: Cooperativa.cl [in Spanish, trans. Mod.MPP, edited]
http://www.cooperativa.cl/noticias/pais/salud/vacunacion/confusam-gobierno-reacciono-tarde-por-meningitis/2012-10-14/141843.html


The National Confederation of Municipal Health Officials (CONFUSAM) accused the Government of a delayed response and negligence when facing the recent increase in cases of meningitis in Chile.

Between January and October 2012, 87 cases of [meningococcal] meningitis type W135 have already been confirmed, while in all of 2011 there were only 73 cases reported.

For Esteban Maturana, leader of the organization [CONFUSAM], the negligence lies in "the existing controls of the Ministry of Health," specifically the "surveillance system which verifies the number of cases, and this system has alerts which signal when there is a health problem."

The Government recently announced a round of vaccines that will arrive in the country on Monday morning [15 Oct 2012], and [vaccination] will be focused on children less than 4 years of age, the population most vulnerable for this disease.

For the senator of the PPD [Partido por la Democracia/Party for Democracy], Guido Girardi, the announcement by the government is important, even if it was late, and he urged authorities to also include an educational campaign. "Better late than never, always. I think the important thing is to begin with a public health action, as has already been announced, [the need for vaccination], but I hope that vaccination [activities] are accompanied by an educational campaign, which I think is as important as the vaccine," he said.

--
