[Guido Girardi Lavin is a Chilean physician and politician. He is currently serving the period between 2006 and 2014 as senator for district No. 7 for Santiago Poniente (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guido_Girardi). He is also serving as the current president of that chamber. - Mod.ML]

******
[2]
Date: Tue 25 Sep 2012
Source: Nacion.cl [in Spanish, machine trans., summ., edited]
http://www.lanacion.cl/minsal-alerta-a-red-hospitalaria-por-agresiva-cepa-que-produce-meningitis/noticias/2012-09-25/140206.html


A total of 73 cases of meningitis have been recorded so far this year [2012] in Chile, a figure that exceeds the notifications for the same period of 2011 (46 cases). The health authority is keeping under surveillance serogroup W135, which has been detected in 42 percent of cases from January [2012] to date. Children under 4 years of age are the most affected group and accounted for 45 percent of all reported cases; children between 5 and 9 years of age accounted for 7 percent; and 45 percent of the cases occurred in people over 20 years of age. 17 cases occurred in children under one year (23 percent), who had the highest incidence rate of 6.7 cases per 100 000 children.

According to the epidemiological report of the Ministry of Health (Minsal), the Region of Valparaiso has the highest incidence rate (0.9 per 100 000 population), followed by the [Santiago] Metropolitan Region. No epidemiological link between the most affected areas has been identified.

There have been 14 deaths (CFR 19 percent) reported this year [2012], higher than expected; 5 of the deaths were due to W135; 1 due to B; 1 due to C, and 3 unidentified.

By this time of year, there are usually between 56 and 60 cases. The Health Secretary, Jorge Diaz, said that the increase in reported cases this year "is small and does not constitute an outbreak."

[Byline: Patricia Schuller G]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[From the news reports above, there are discrepancies in the number of cases and the meningococcal serogroups that are causing meningococcal meningitis in Chile. A clarification would be appreciated.

There are 5 common meningococcal serogroups, based on the antigenic specificity of their capsular polysaccharides: A, B, C, W135, and Y, and a 6th type (X) has recently emerged in Africa. Capsular polysaccharide or protein conjugate vaccines can immunize against disease caused by serogroups A, C, W135, and Y. Serogroup B remains a major cause of severe invasive disease in infants and adolescents worldwide; but, because the serogroup B polysaccharide resembles the human neural cell adhesion molecule, the serogroup B capsular polysaccharide is poorly immunogenic. To control an outbreak, WHO recommends mass vaccination with the appropriate meningococcal vaccine in every involved district in an attempt to induce herd immunity, whereby transmission is blocked when a critical percentage of the population has been vaccinated (see http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs141/en/). Meningococcal vaccines will only protect against meningitis due to the meningococcal polysaccharide serogroups that the vaccine contains. The components and the type of the vaccine being used in Chile are not stated in the news reports above.

The Valparaiso Region and Santiago Metropolitan Region (or simply Metropolitan Region), 2 of Chile's 15 administrative divisions, are adjacent to each other in the center of Chile. A map of Chile's regions can be seen at http://www.cybertruffle.org.uk/chilfung/chile_regions.gif.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Chile can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/1Aht. - Mod.ML]
